{{Infobox protected area | name = Bemaraha National Park | iucn_category = II | photo =Tsingy_de_Bemaraha_Strict_Nature_Reserve.jpg | photo_caption = A karst limestone formation, known as tsingy in Malagasy | map = Madagascar | relief = yes | map_width = 220 | map_caption = Location of Bemaraha National Park | location = Western Madagascar | nearest_city = Morondava, Antsalova | embedded1 = {{designation list | embed=yes | designation1 = WHS | designation1_offname = Tsingy de Bemaraha Strict Nature Reserve | designation1_date = 1990 <small>(14th [[World Heritage Committee|session]])</small> | designation1_type = Natural | designation1_criteria = vii, x | designation1_number = [http://whc.unesco.org/en/list/494rev 494rev] | designation1_free1name = State Party | designation1_free1value = [[Madagascar]] | designation1_free2name = Region | designation1_free2value = [[List of World Heritage Sites in Africa|Africa]] }} | coordinates = {{coord|18|40|S|44|45|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}} | area = 666 km² | established = 1997 | visitation_num = approx. 6000 | visitation_year = 2005 | governing_body = Parcs Nationaux Madagascar - ANGAP }}
'''Tsingy de Bemaraha Strict Nature Reserve''' is a [[nature reserve]] located near the western coast of [[Madagascar]] in [[Melaky]] Region at {{coord|18|40|S|44|45|E|type:landmark|name=Tsingy}}. The area was listed as a [[UNESCO World Heritage Site]] in 1990 due to the unique [[geography]], preserved [[mangrove]] forests, and wild bird and [[lemur]] populations.<ref name="Unesco">{{cite web |url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/list/494 |title=Tsingy de Bemaraha Strict Nature Reserve |work=[[UNESCO]] |accessdate=2009-11-01 |format=}}</ref><ref name="Shea">{{cite news | last = Shea | first = Neil | title = Living On a Razor's Edge: Madagascar's labyrinth of stone | work=[[National Geographic (magazine)|National Geographic]] | date = November 2009 | url = http://ngm.nationalgeographic.com/print/2009/11/stone-forest/shea-text | accessdate = 2009-11-01 }}</ref>
==National Park== The southern end of the protected area has subsequently been changed into the [[Tsingy de Bemaraha National Park]], covering {{convert|666|km2|mi2}}. The northern end of the protected area remains as a strict nature reserve (Réserve Naturelle Intégrale) covering {{convert|853|km2|mi2}}. It is characterised by needle-shaped limestone formations, above cliffs over the [[Manambolo River]]. <ref>{{cite web|title=21 World Heritage Sites you have probably never heard of|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/travelnews/10999939/21-World-Heritage-Sites-you-have-probably-never-heard-of.html|publisher=Daily Telegraph}}</ref> The incredibly sharp limestone formations can cut through equipment and flesh easily, which makes traversing them extremely difficult. The word "Tsingy" is derived from a local word meaning "the place where one cannot walk barefoot".
==Tourism== Tourists can access the national park by road from [[Morondava]], a town 150&nbsp;km south of the park. Limited access is also possible from the town of [[Antsalova]], which can be reached by plane from [[Antananarivo]] or [[Mahajanga]].
